[{"location":"#AffineA","page":"Home","title":"AffineA","text":"Documentation for AffineA.","category":"section"},{"location":"#AffineA.AffineA","page":"Home","title":"AffineA.AffineA","text":"This package implements:\n\nthe type PPerm, the periodic permutations of the integers.\nthe  function  coxeter_PPerm_group(n)  (or coxPPerm(n)), the Coxeter group of type AÌƒâ‚™â‚‹â‚, as a group of PPerms of period n.\nthe function DualBraidMonoid for such groups.\n\nIt is based on the papers\n\n[Digne, F.] \"Presentations duales pour les groupes de tresses de type affine A\", Comment. Math. Helv. 81 (2006) 23â€“47\n[Shi] The Kazhdan-Lusztig cells in certain affine Weyl groups  Springer LNM 1179 (1986) \n\nÂ©FranÃ§ois Digne (2007) for the  mathematics, FranÃ§ois Digne and Jean Michel for the code.\n\nInstalling\n\nTo install this package, start Julia, enter package mode with ], and then do\n\n(@v1.12) pkg> add https://github.com/jmichel7/AffineA.jl\n\nexit package mode with backspace and then do\n\njulia> using Chevie, AffineA\n\nand you are set up.\n\nTo update later to the latest version, do\n\n(@v1.12) pkg> update AffineA\n\nAn example:\n\njulia> W=coxPPerm(3) # The group AÌƒâ‚‚ as periodic permutations of period 3.\ncoxeter_PPerm_group(3)\n\njulia> l=elements(W,3) # elements of Coxeter length 3\n9-element Vector{PPerm}:\n (2,3â‚‹â‚)\n (1,2)â‚(3)â‚‹â‚\n (1)â‚‹â‚(2,3)â‚\n (1,3)\n (1,3)â‚(2)â‚‹â‚\n (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n (1)â‚(2,3â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚\n (1,3â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(2)â‚\n (1,2â‚‹â‚)\n\njulia> print(l[6]) # the images of 1:3 by the 6th element\nPPerm(Int16[-1, 1, 6])\n\njulia> mod1.([-1, 1, 6],3) # the image in ð”–â‚ƒ\n3-element Vector{Int64}:\n 2\n 1\n 3\n\njulia> l[6] # printed as product of cycles with shifts -1 and 1 (sum 0). 2â‚‹â‚ is 2-3\nPPerm(3): (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n\njulia> B=DualBraidMonoid(W) # The Coxeter element is W(1,2,3)\nDualBraidMonoid(coxeter_PPerm_group(3),c=[1, 2, 3])\n\njulia> b=prod(B.(refls(W,1:7))) # the product in B of 7 dual atoms\nc.4.5.46\n\njulia> print(b)\nB(2,4,3,4,5,4,6)\n\njulia> refls(W,2:5) # the corresponding reflections\n4-element Vector{PPerm}:\n (2,3)\n (1,3â‚‹â‚)\n (1,3)\n (1,2â‚‹â‚)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"module"},{"location":"#AffineA.PPerm","page":"Home","title":"AffineA.PPerm","text":"a PPerm represents a shiftless periodic permutation f of the integers\n\nperiodic of period n means f(i+n)=f(i)+n\nthen permutation means all f(i) are distinct mod n.\nno shift means sum(f.(1:n))==sum(1:n)\n\nit is represented in field d as the Vector [f(1),â€¦,f(n)]. The default constructor  takes a  vector of  integers, and  checks its  validity if the keyword check=true is given.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"#AffineA.PPerm-Tuple{Integer, Vararg{Any}}","page":"Home","title":"AffineA.PPerm","text":"PPerm(n,câ‚,â€¦,câ‚—;check=true)  constructs a PPerm of period n by giving its decomposition into cycles.\n\ncycles cáµ¢ are given as pairs (iâ‚,â€¦,iâ‚–)=>d representing the  permutation iâ‚â†¦ iâ‚‚â†¦ â€¦â†¦ iâ‚–â†¦ iâ‚+d*n.  =>d can be omitted when d==0 and (iâ‚,)=>d can be abbreviated to iâ‚=>d. \n\nAn iâ±¼ itself may be given as a pair v=>d representing v+n*d.\n\nThe  argument is  tested for  validity if  check=true; in  particular the cycles must be disjoint mod. n.\n\njulia> PPerm([-1,1,6])\nPPerm(3): (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n\njulia> PPerm(3,(1,2=>-1)=>-1,3=>1)\nPPerm(3): (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n\njulia> PPerm(3,(1,-1)=>-1,3=>1)\nPPerm(3): (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#PermGroups.Perms.cycles-Tuple{PPerm}","page":"Home","title":"PermGroups.Perms.cycles","text":"cycles(a::PPerm)\n\nThe non-trivial cycles of a PPerm; each cycle is returned as a pair (iâ‚,â€¦,iâ‚–)=>d and  is normalized such that mod1(iâ‚,n) is the smallest of the  mod1(iâ±¼,n) and 1â‰¤iâ‚â‰¤n.\n\njulia> cycles(PPerm([-1,1,6]))\n2-element Vector{Pair{Vector{Int64}, Int64}}:\n [1, -1] => -1\n     [3] => 1\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#AffineA.coxeter_PPerm_group","page":"Home","title":"AffineA.coxeter_PPerm_group","text":"coxeter_PPerm_group(n::Integer) returns W(AÌƒâ‚™â‚‹â‚) as a group of PPerm of period n.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#Chevie.PermRoot.refls-Tuple{AffineA.Atilde, Integer}","page":"Home","title":"Chevie.PermRoot.refls","text":"refls(W::Atilde,i::Integer)\n\nreturns  the i-th reflection of  W. Reflections (a,bâ±¼) are enumerated by  lexicographical order of (j,a,b-a) with j nonnegative; however when a>b  this reflection  is printed  (b,aâ‚‹â±¼). i  can also be a Vector; then the corresponding list of reflections is returned.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#Chevie.Garside.DualBraidMonoid-Tuple{AffineA.Atilde}","page":"Home","title":"Chevie.Garside.DualBraidMonoid","text":"DualBraidMonoid(W::Atilde)\n\nIf W=coxeter_PPerm_group(n), constructs the dual braid monoid for AÌƒâ‚™â‚‹â‚ and the Coxeter element c=PPerm([1-n;3:n;2+n]). If M=DualBraidMonoid(W),  used as a  function, M(w) returns  an element of the  dual  braid  monoid  if  wâˆˆW  belongs  to  the interval [1,c], and nothing otherwise.\n\njulia> W=coxPPerm(3);l=elements(W,3)\n9-element Vector{PPerm}:\n (2,3â‚‹â‚)\n (1,2)â‚(3)â‚‹â‚\n (1)â‚‹â‚(2,3)â‚\n (1,3)\n (1,3)â‚(2)â‚‹â‚\n (1,2â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(3)â‚\n (1)â‚(2,3â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚\n (1,3â‚‹â‚)â‚‹â‚(2)â‚\n (1,2â‚‹â‚)\n\njulia> B=DualBraidMonoid(W);B.(l)\n9-element Vector{Union{Nothing, GarsideElt{PPerm, AffineA.AffaDualBraidMonoid{PPerm, AffineA.Atilde}}}}:\n 6\n nothing\n c\n 4\n nothing\n nothing\n nothing\n nothing\n 5\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
